INFLUENZA ACTIVITY DURING 1995-1996 SEASON

Based on reports from National Influenza Centres to WHO

Situation as at 3 January 1996: Influenza activity has reached a peak in
the Czech Republic, southern France and the UK. In many other European
countries influenza activity increased during December. Influenza A
continues to predominate. Both H1N1 and H3N2 subtypes have been detected
but the H3N2 subtype has been more widely reported. Influenza A(H1N1) has
been the most common influenza type diagnosed in Canada, Poland and
Switzerland and in parts of France.

Since 1 October 1995, cases of influenza A and/or B have been reported in
Africa: Madagascar (A/H3N2)
Americas: Canada (A/H1N1), Chile (A), USA (A/H1N1, A/H3N2, B)
Asia: Islamic Rep. Iran (A), Israel (A/H3N2, A/H1N1, B)
Europe: Belgium(A/H3N2), Czech Republic(A/H3N2), Finland (A/H3N2), France
(A/H3N2, A/H1N1), Germany(A/H3N2, A/H1N1), Iceland(A/H3N2), Italy(A/H3N2),
Latvia(A/H3N2), Netherlands(A/H3N2), Norway(A/H3N2), Poland(A/H1N1),
Portugal(A), Romania (A/H1N1, A/H3N2, B), Slovak Republic (A/H3N2),
Spain(A/H3N2), Sweden (A/H3N2), Switzerland(A/H1N1, A/H3N2, B), UK (A/H1N1,
A/H3N2, B)

Oceania: Australia (B), New Zealand (A/H3N2, B)

The Directors of the WHO Collaborating Centres for Reference and Research
on Influenza met in Geneva 13-14 February 1995 and recommended the
following composition of vaccines to use in the 1995-1996 season:
A/Johannesburg/33/94(H3N2), A/Singapore/6/86(H1N1) and B/Beijing/184/93.
The A/Singapore/6/86(H1N1)-like strain used in most vaccines is
A/Texas/1/86. The full recommendations were published in Weekly
Epidemiological Record, No. 8 on 24 February 1995.

